		<bioghist>
			<head>Biographical Note</head>
			<p><persname>Harold O. ("Hal") Lewis Jr. (1931-2016)</persname> was born on <date normal="1931-07-10">July 10, 1931</date>, to <persname>Harold O. Lewis Sr.</persname> and <persname>Catherine Cardozo Lewis</persname>. His father was a history professor at Howard University who gifted Hal his first camera. Hal began photographing trains as a junior in high school in the <date normal="1945/1949">late 1940s</date>.</p>
			<p>Hal earned his undergraduate degree in engineering from <corpname>Purdue University</corpname> in <geogname>West Lafayette, Indiana</geogname>, in <date>1953</date>. During college he worked as a <occupation>fireman</occupation> on steam locomotives and photographed the region's railroads. He married <persname>Thalia Thomas</persname> in <date>1954</date>.</p>
			<p>Following graduation, Hal pursued a career in aeronautics. He worked as an <occupation>aeronautical engineer</occupation> for the <corpname>Boeing Company</corpname> in <geogname>Seattle, Washington</geogname>, from <date normal="1953/1958">1953-58</date>. <date normal="1958/1989">From 1958 until his retirement in 1989</date>, Hal worked for <corpname>Lockheed Martin</corpname> in <geogname>Sunnyvale, California</geogname>. He earned an MBA from <corpname>San Jose State University</corpname> while working for Lockheed.</p>
			<p>Hal's photographs have appeared in <title render="italic">Classic Trains</title> and <title render="italic">Railfan &amp; Railroad</title> magazines.In addition to photographing railroads, Hal made railroad audio recordings. He started recording audio as a hobby in <date>1957</date>, and later sold recordings through a business he started with another recordist, <corpname>L&amp;H Railsonics</corpname>.</p>
			<p>Following his retirement from Lockheed in <date>1989</date>, Hal volunteered with the Central Coast Chapter of the <corpname>National Railroad Historical Society</corpname> and the <corpname>Pacific Limited Group</corpname>. He received the Gerald M. Best Senior Achievement Award from the Railway &amp; Locomotive Historical Society in <date>2013</date>.</p>
			<p>Hal passed away on <date normal="2016-08-27">August 27, 2016</date>.</p>
		</bioghist>
		<scopecontent>
			<head>Scope and Content Note</head>
			<p>The Hal Lewis collection, 1947-1998, consists of about 1,600 railroad photographs from the United States, Mexico, Canada, Ecuador, and Brazil, shot by Hal Lewis. Contents include about 750 black-and-white negatives, 800 35mm color slides, and 85 4x6 and 8.5x11 inch prints. Strengths include steam locomotives in the American mid-Antlantic, midwest, and west coast regions, such as on the New York Central Railroad, Baltimore &amp; Ohio Railway, Northern Pacific Railway, Southern Pacific Railroad, and West Side Lumber Company Railroad.</p>
		</scopecontent>
		<arrangement>
			<head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
			<p>The collection is arranged by format, following Lewis' original order.</p>
		</arrangement>
